  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 5f7201a12d95ffc409449d95f23cf332, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: UnityEngine.UI::UnityEngine.UI.Text
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 0.19607843, g: 0.19607843, b: 0.19607843, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_FontData:
    m_Font: {fileID: 10102, guid: 0000000000000000e000000000000000, type: 0}
    m_FontSize: 26
    m_FontStyle: 1
    m_BestFit: 0
    m_MinSize: 10
    m_MaxSize: 40
    m_Alignment: 6
    m_AlignByGeometry: 0
    m_RichText: 1
    m_HorizontalOverflow: 0
    m_VerticalOverflow: 0
    m_LineSpacing: 1
  m_Text: 'Senior Dev: Cookies! Who doesn''t love cookies? But don''t be fooled by
    this type of cookie, it is not eddible!


    Think of a web cookie as a "reminder"
    given to your device by the website, on which may be written your preferences
    or role for that site.


    Whenever you navigate the same website, it reads
    your reminder and knows exactly how to treat you!

    For example, the site
    might give you a cookie named "role" which has the value "guest", this will tell
    the website "A guest is visiting the site, I will deliver the guest page."


    While
    these are neat for providing memory for a website, if these are not created securely,
    someone might be able to trick the website in malicious ways.


    !! See the
    current cookie in your browser, "auth level:user"?  change it to "admin" and
    see what happens!

'
